### Hierarchy - Dutch enacted law {#hierarchy---dutch-enacted-law .unnumbered}

a)  Treaties

b)  Charter for the Kingdom of NL

c)  Constitution

d)  Statutes;

    i.  Acts of Parliament

    ii. Order in Council (Royal Decree / Govt Regulation)

    iii. Ministerial Regulation

e)  Provincial / Municipal / Waterboards By-laws

#### Conflict rules {#conflict-rules .unnumbered}

1.  Higher rule prevails over lower rule - lex superiori derogat legi
    > inferiori

2.  Newer rule prevails over earlier rule - lex posterior derogat legi
    > priori

3.  Specific rule prevails over general rule - lex specialis derogat
    > legi generali

### **Unwritten law** {#unwritten-law .unnumbered}

#### Case law

= rulings of judges

-   no formal principle of precedent - no stare decisis, but in practice
    > courts abide rulings of highest court (e.g. Supreme Court)

#### Customary law

-   bottom-up;

-   usus (practiced uniformly and consistently) &

-   opinio iuris / necessitatis (should be a binding rule; regarded as
    > required by law)

#### Principles

-   supplement law: no one can benefit from his/her own wrongdoing
    > (Estoppel principle)

-   general principles of good governance (honoring promises)

