# W2: Constitutional law {#w2-constitutional-law .unnumbered}

...is the part of public law which defines the organization of a certain
territory, e.g. the structure, roles, powers, branches (e.g.
legislative, executive, judiciary) of law within a state, as well as the
relationship between states and citizens.

## Constitutional law {#constitutional-law .unnumbered}

1.  Constitution (Kingdom of the Netherlands: The NL + Aruba + Curaçao +
    > Sint Maarten),

2.  Custom (e.g. the confidence rule - not written down),

3.  Case law (decisions of the Supreme Court).

-   not everything is in writing due to politics (needs to be flexible)

-   NL has a **monist** system → a treaty does not have to be
    > transformed into national law; if it contains needed provisions -
    > can be referred to immediately

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
-   provisions are binding after they are published (Art. 93 C.) and
    > rules regarding such publications are laid down by Act of
    > Parliament (Art. 95 C.)

## State {#state .unnumbered}

1.  a defined territory

2.  permanent population

3.  effective and independent authority / government, can exert
    > influence over a population

-   does **not** need to be recognized by other states in order to be a
    > state

### Unitary state

-   central government supreme, e.g. France

-   any subnational units exercise only powers delegated by their
    > central government

### Federation

-   a union of partially self-governing states / regions under a central
    > / federal government

-   The Kingdom of the NL, The US, Germany etc.

-   government has many more competences than in a confederation

### Confederation

-   supremacy of individual states that unite for a common action

-   marginal loss of sovereignty (Russia / Belarus); marginal
    > competences that are shared

-   competences exactly described; if not listed in a Constitution - do
    > not have it

### Presidential systems {#presidential-systems .unnumbered}

-   the head of the executive elected independently with a mandate of
    > his own

-   not accountable to Congress in the sense of confidence rule

-   whether Congress has confidence in him or not, the President stays
    > in power

### Parliamentary systems {#parliamentary-systems .unnumbered}

-   the head of the executive owes the continuation of his office to the
    > parliament and is accountable to parliament in the sense of
    > confidence rule

-   PMs / chancellors can be voted out of office via a parliamentary
    > *vote of no confidence*

### The (EU) Netherlands {#the-eu-netherlands .unnumbered}

1.  Constitutional monarchy (chapter 2 C.)

2.  Parliamentary democracy (chapter 3 C.)

3.  Decentralized unitary state (chapter 7 C.)

Dutch Constitution

