## Procedural administrative law {#procedural-administrative-law .unnumbered}

### Invoking legal protection in administrative courts  {#invoking-legal-protection-in-administrative-courts .unnumbered}

**3 requirements**:

1.  Appealable / contestable orders (8:3 GALA)

-   administrative decision (including refusal) and administrative
    > measures

-   always check - is it a **valid order** in the first place? 1:3(1)
    > GALA

-   other orders: appealable to civil courts (e.g. policy rules)

2.  Who can appeal?

-   (in)directly interested party (1:2 GALA) - interest is directly
    > affected by an order;

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
-   directly interested party: addressee of the order (person/object),
    > recipient of right/duty

-   interested third party: concern should be:

1)  own → not caretaker

2)  personal → distinguishable from mass

3)  objective → not merely emotional

4)  current → not dependent on future events

5)  directly linked to decision → causal connection

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
3.  Preliminary: **notice of objection**

-   Administrative authority takes original decision

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
-   interested party objects to 1st decision

-   hearing + advice from committee to AA

-   decision after objection

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
-   threshold before court; free of charge; art. 8:1 and 7:1 GALA

-   full reconsideration by AA (usually the original decision maker):
    > judicial and functional

-   must contain: name, address, date, description, objections,
    > signature (6:5 GALA)

-   explain point of view at hearing

### Administrative appeal (judiciary) {#administrative-appeal-judiciary .unnumbered}

1)  Administrative proceedings

> 1st instance → **Notice of objection** - procedure
>
> 2nd instance → Appeal at **District Court**, administrative Sector
> (8:1, 8:3, 8:7 GALA)
>
> 3rd and last instance → **Highest courts**:

-   Council of State - administrative law division (8:105 GALA)

-   Central Appeals Court

-   Trade and Industry Court

2)  Civil proceedings (oldest courts, leftovers)

### Outcome administrative appeal {#outcome-administrative-appeal .unnumbered}

1)  possible verdicts administrative judge

-   not competent → other court jurisdiction

-   not admissible → appeal filed too late; not an interested party

-   unfounded → plaintiff loses

-   well-founded → authority loses

2)  after verdict well-founded

-   annulment/quashing decision → back to AA

-   annulment + judge replaces decision himself

# W4: Criminal law {#w4-criminal-law .unnumbered}

*Principle of legality*

-   **nulla poena sine lege**: no act or omission which did not
    > constitute an offense under the law at the time of its commission
    > shall be punishable by law (art. 16 C. & 1(1) PC)

-   International law: art. 22 & 23 Rome Statute of the ICC & art. 7(1)
    > ECHR

-   nullum crimen, nulla poena sine praevia lege poenali: no crime can
    > be committed, nor punishment imposed without a pre-existing penal
    > law; implies:

    -   no retroactive effect (lex praevia)

    -   written description of the guilty act (lex scripta)

    -   precise legislation (lex certa)

    -   ban on reasoning by analogy (lex stricta)

*Presumption of innocence*

-   innocent until proven guilty; the convicted does not have to prove
    > he is innocent, that is the job of the attorney - burden of proof
    > with prosecutor (art. 6(2) ECHR)

