# W5: Private law {#w5-private-law .unnumbered}

The area of law pertaining to the relationships between **juridical
persons** (natural persons or private & public legal persons, including
corporations), as opposed to relations between the state and private
persons. **Horizontal** relationships (differ from public law).

**Juridical person** = an independent bearer of rights and duties and
therefore subject to the law

## Patrimonial law {#patrimonial-law .unnumbered}

Concerns rights with a particular financial value; patrimonium:

1.  personal rights **+** (law of obligations)

2.  debts **-** (law of obligations)

3.  real rights (law of property)

Law of property: tangible → physical, and intangible → e.g. copyright

Financial value can be negative → **bankruptcy**

### The Dutch Civil Code {#the-dutch-civil-code .unnumbered}

Stratified structure; general → specific

Follows the old Roman distinction between *in rem* and *in personam*:

1.  *in rem* - right to an object; tangible - real rights (Book 5) and
    > intangible (e.g. copyright)

2.  *in personam* - right to a performance by another person

**Book 2**: law of legal persons, (un)limited companies, the foundation
and association

**Book 3**: general definitions and rules relevant to patrimonial law;
how to establish rights to a property, provisions related to juridical
acts (offer and acceptance, representation) etc.

**Book 5**: property law: ownership and other rights concerning
(im)movable objects

**Book 6**: general part of the law dealt with in book 7 (contract of
sale, employment etc.)

## Concepts & definitions {#concepts-definitions .unnumbered}

### Offer {#offer .unnumbered}

1.  statement includes the major elements of the contract to be entered
    > in

2.  all the other party has to do is say 'yes' and the contract is
    > formed

3.  if essential elements missing → invitation to make an offer

\*offer may be subject to the fulfillment of a condition (e.g. time
limit making it irrevocable)

**Revocable offer**: An offer is revocable, unless there is evidence to
the contrary (e.g. it mentions a term / date); the offeror will not be
able to revoke the offer during its term. If the offeree accepts the
offer before the deadline, a contract is concluded even if offeror
changes his mind.

###  {#section-3 .unnumbered}

### Obligation {#obligation .unnumbered}

a.  a legal relation between at least two persons

b.  which entitles one party (creditor) to a performance of the other
    > party (debtor)

c.  that needs to be performed and for which the law usually provides a
    > remedy (action)

d.  exception: 'natural obligation' (6:3 DCC) & Statute of Limitation

e.  result → '**bond of law**' = vinculum iuris

