## Contract law {#contract-law .unnumbered}

(Book 3, art. 37 DCC)

### Freedom of contract {#freedom-of-contract .unnumbered}

a.  freedom from formal requirements (written or oral)

b.  freedom in choice of contract partner(s)

c.  freedom in choice of obligations (expand or limit obligations; e.g.
    > guarantee or conditions → change in liability status)

d.  freedom regarding other content

Freedom is **not** unlimited (art. 3:40 DCC)

### General requirements for a valid contract {#general-requirements-for-a-valid-contract .unnumbered}

1.  capacity (3:32 DCC) - party capable to perform; mental impairment
    > (art. 3:34 DCC)

2.  permissible (3:40 DCC) - not against the law

3.  consensus (6:217 jo 3:33 DCC) - offer + acceptance = both parties'
    > will. If not:

    a.  will not aligned with the statement (3:35 DCC) - principle of
        > good faith (3:11 DCC)

    b.  will aligned with the statement, but vitiated consent

4.  determinability of obligations (6:227 DCC)

Declaration of intent: juridical act requires an intent revealed (Art.
3:33 DCC) to the other party who had good reason to rely on it (Art.
3:35 DCC)

N.B. Art. 6:217 includes the definition of a contract

