-   accession - states which join later

3.  Treaty enters into force if **enough States consent** to be bound

International law

-   1969 VCLT

-   pacta sunt servanda (Art. 26)

-   international customary law

#### Custom

1.  **Usus** ('sufficiently widespread and uniform' practice) -
    > objective

2.  **Opinio iuris** (belief that it was carried out as a legal
    > obligation) - subjective

Examples:

-   Diplomatic immunity (and what it entails) → Vienna Convention on
    > Diplomatic Relations

-   Law of the sea → UN Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS)

Custom can become treaty law:

-   Custom - territorial waters: reach of cannons (3 miles); moved to 12
    > miles

-   UNCLOS - took effect in 1994; territorial sea up to 12 miles

\*Example of custom: Caroline test of determining whether self-defense
is justified; elements needed - proportionality and subsidiarity

#### General principles of law

-   implemented when no treaty or custom exists

-   common in almost all legal systems

Examples:

1.  good faith - nuclear test case (1974)

2.  abuse of power

3.  reparation

#### Binding decisions of international organizations

-   not stated in Art. 38 SICJ

-   e.g. Security Council of the United Nations (art. 25 UN Charter)

-   the fact that decisions are binding adds a supranational factor to
    > the UN (except to the permanent members)

### Hierarchy {#hierarchy .unnumbered}

There is no formal hierarchy among categories of sources; **however**:

1.  In a conflict of treaties, the UN Charter prevails over other
    > international sources (Art. 103 UN Charter)

2.  Peremptory norms, ius cogens, always take precedence;

-   norms that are so important that they cannot be derogated from if
    > there's a conflict with other obligations; e.g. prohibition from
    > torture, genocide etc.

-   any treaty which is not concluded in accordance with ius cogens is
    > automatically void, according to Art. 53 VCLT

