        > member states (art. 25 UN Charter)

-   The Council shall call upon parties to settle their disputes
    > peacefully (art. 33(2) UN Charter); if not possible: art. 39 UN
    > Charter: determine aggression, take measures;

    -   art. 41 UN Charter: measures not involving the use of armed
        > force; if insufficient:

    -   art. 42 UN Charter: measures involving the use of armed force

#### **International Court of Justice**

(art. 92 ff. UN Charter)

a.  art. 92 UN Charter: conflict between states, no mandatory
    > jurisdiction (art. 36 SICJ)

b.  art. 94 UN Charter: compliance with ICJ judgments

c.  art. 96 UN Charter: advice, at the request of the SC / GA / other
    > bodies

d.  art. 36 SICJ: jurisdiction if:

-   both parties voluntarily submit the case to the ICJ ('all cases
    > which the parties refer to it'); art. 36(1) SICJ - ad hoc

-   if ICJ jurisdiction is provided for in 'treaties and conventions in
    > force' - ante hoc

#### **Secretary-General**

(art. 97 ff. UN Charter)

-   head of the Secretariat and chief administrator of the UN

-   candidates for Secretary-General are nominated by the Security
    > Council and appointed by the General Assembly for maximum 2 5-year
    > terms

-   Secretary-Generals are not from countries that are permanent members
    > of the SC

## International human rights law {#international-human-rights-law .unnumbered}

European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR)

-   Convention of the Council of Europe

-   Mainly civil and political rights (e.g. art. 6, art. 8 etc.)

European Court on Human Rights (ECtHR)

-   jurisdiction: art. 32 ECHR

-   admissibility: art. 35 ECHR

### ECtHR grounds for suspending cases {#ecthr-grounds-for-suspending-cases .unnumbered}

1.  Domestic remedies not exhausted (art. 35(1) ECHR)

2.  Time limits for submitting case not respected (art. 35(1) ECHR)

3.  Application is anonymous (art. 35(2) ECHR)

4.  Application is incompatible with the provisions of the Convention
    > (art. 35(3) jo 1 ECHR)

5.  Applicant has not suffered a significant disadvantage (art. 35(3)
    > ECHR)

6.  Case manifestly ill-founded

### Categories of human rights {#categories-of-human-rights .unnumbered}

#### Civil and political rights

a.  protect the individual from the state

b.  enable the individual to participate in the political life of the
    > state

-   e.g. the right to life, prohibition against torture, fair trial,
    > freedom of expression, vote

-   enshrined in general human rights instruments (UDHR, ICCPR, ECHR)
    > and require the state to abstain from interfering with the
    > enjoyment of these rights

-   require immediate realization by states (art. 2 ICCPR)

#### Economic, social and cultural rights

-   safeguard the individual's socio-economic well-being, cultural
    > identity and freedom

```{=html}
<!-- -->
```
-   e.g. right to work and adequate working conditions, social security,
    > education...

-   sometimes call for abstention by states as well, e.g. the right to
    > strike

-   permit progressive rather than immediate realization

-   entail an obligation of conduct (taking steps) rather than
    > obligation of result

#### Collective rights

-   belong to certain groups considered to be vulnerable and in need of
    > special protection

-   e.g. right to self-determination of people, land rights for
    > Indigenous people, right to a healthy environment, somewhat
    > intangible right to development

-   cannot be claimed by individual members of that group, only by the
    > group as a whole

-   some human rights that are essentially collective in nature are
    > sometimes invoked as individual rights in practice; e.g. right to
    > a healthy environment in the Urgenda case
